defaultWritten sdefaultubmission from the Electrical Safety Roundtabledefault (BRC 41)default&#xa0;defaultSummarydefaultThe Electrical Safety Roundtable (ESR) was initially formed in response to widespread concern over poor promotion of competent registered electricians
default and a lack of Building Regulation enforcement. It is run by and independent secretariat has four board members and is chaired by Chris Bielby, Chair of Trustees at the Gas Safety Trust.  The group works collaboratively with industry and other relevant interested stakeholders to improve electrical safety in the home. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ESR notes that whilst awareness of the Building Regulations and Competent Person Schemes has been historically low, improving enforcement of building regulations and simplifying the message to consumers of the benefits of using a Competent, Registered Electrician is the best approach to improving this. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHistorically, the standards required of competent electricians have varied. The ESR believes that this will be remedied to a significant degree by the new DCLG conditions of authorisation that all CPS providers must adhere to by June 2014 which include compliance with EAS 2012 standards, which have been revised and improved compared to the 2010 ones. However, we also note the current inadequacy of the specification’s emphasis on competent 
defaultenterprises 
defaultrather than individuals. 
defaultThe ESR is of the view that requiring all electricians carrying out notifiable work under the Building Regulations to demonstrate their competence individually would improve levels of safety, as is the case in Ireland.
default&#xa0;
defaultDCLG currently sets strict, uniform terms for all Competent Person Scheme providers
default and t
defaulthere is evidence of the positive impact of competition between CPS providers (EC Harris Report 2012)
default. 
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ESR believes that better promotion of competent, registered electricians is vital to improving levels of consumer awareness and therefore safety. It 
defaultsupports the idea of 
defaulta single consumer facing register, fed into by all electrical Competent Person Scheme providers to retain the positive aspects of competition.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ESR considers that the issue of DCLG supervision has already been addressed; from June 2014, the responsibility for scheme supervision will transfer to UKAS and all scheme providers will be required to achieve/maintain UKAS accreditation to standard BS EN ISO/IEC 17065:2012 by that date.
default As a minimum, UKAS has committed to conducting surveillance of CPS providers annually and ensuring they are fully
default r
defaulte-assessed every fourth year.
